    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.11.21-22_0001" />
                
                <fw type="curatorial">21</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">JAMES H. COOK
                        <lb/>
                    HAROLD J. COOK
                        <lb/>
                
                    THE AGATE SPRINGS RANCH
                        <lb/>
                    AGATE, NEBRASKA</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>July 8th 1924</dateline>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. Jno <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Branson</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Missouri</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Your letter of June 21st to my son, was handed to me, as he was just starting away on <add>a</add> trip &#8212; On account of an accident which injured my eyes I have been unable to write to you sooner &#8212;
                
                In answer to your question as to Crazy Horse's "Devils Song," can only say that "Big Bat," who was with him when he died, (and was the only white man present, at that <add>time,</add> who could understand <hi rend="underline">what was said, or sung</hi>, by Crazy Horse,) has often told me, that the only words used by the old warrior when dying, and in a semiunconcious state, were, "Father I want to 
                
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.11.21-22_0002"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">22</fw>
               
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps"><unclear cert="high">JAM</unclear>ES H. COOK
                        <lb/>
                    <unclear cert="high">H</unclear>AROLD J. COOK
                        <lb/>
                    
                    THE AGATE SPRINGS RANCH
                        <lb/>
                    AGATE, NEBRASKA</hi>
                </fw>
                
                    see You," He repeated these words several times in a tone which might be interpreted as a <hi rend="underline">chant</hi>,</p> 
                
                <p>From my observation, and all I can learn on the subject from the ones who should <hi rend="underline">know</hi>, the "Death Song," of indians, when dying such a death as Crazy Horse, has been greatly <hi rend="underline">overworked</hi> by writers.</p>
                
                <p><hi rend="underline">"<unclear>Taint</unclear> human nature</hi>."</p>
                
                <p>I am glad to know that, The Song of the Indian Wars &#8212; is being completed &#8212; Surely I will be most interested in seeing it for I know it will be the best thing of its kind ever written.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Ever, very sincerely yours</salute>
                
                    <signed>James H. Cook</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <postscript><p>Kindly let me hear your opinion as to what I have written about "Death Song."</p></postscript>
                
            </div1>
